  <page>
    <title>Reds</title>
      <minor />
      <comment>External links per MoS.</comment>
      <text xml:space="preserve">''See also [Cincinnati Reds]''
{{Infobox Film | name = Reds
  | image = Reds 1981.jpg
  | caption = ''Reds'' movie poster
  | director = [Warren Beatty]
  | producer = Warren Beatty
  | writer = Warren Beatty<br />[Trevor Griffiths]
  | starring = Warren Beatty<br />[Diane Keaton]
  | music =
  | cinematography =
  | editing =
  | distributor = [Paramount Pictures]
  | released = [December 4], [1981] ([USA])
  | runtime = 194 min.
  | language = [English language|English]<br />[Russian language|Russian]<br />[German language|German]
  | budget = $35,000,000 US (est.)
  | imdb_id = 0082979
}}
'''''Reds''''' is a [1981] [Film|movie] starring [Warren Beatty] and [Diane Keaton]. It centers on the life of [John Reed (journalist)|John Reed], the [Communist], [journalism|journalist] and writer who chronicled the [Russian Revolution of 1917|Russian Revolution] in his book ''[Ten Days that Shook the World (book)|Ten Days that Shook the World]''.

Besides Beatty and Keaton, the movie stars [Edward Herrmann], [Jerzy Kosinski], [Jack Nicholson], [Paul Sorvino], [Maureen Stapleton], [Ramon Bieri], [Nicolas Coster] and [M. Emmet Walsh].  It was adapted by Warren Beatty, [Peter S. Feibleman] (uncredited), [Trevor Griffiths], [Elaine May] (uncredited) and [Jeremy Pikser] from Reed's memoir. It was directed by Beatty. It also stars (as witnesses from past events on and before WWI) the celebrated radical educator and peace activist 98-year old [Scott Nearing] (1883-1983), author [Dorothy Frooks] (1896-1997) and reporter and author [George Seldes] (1890-1995).  It was nominated for [Academy Award for Best Picture|Best Picture], but lost to [Chariots of Fire].

==Awards==

The movie won [Academy Awards] for:
* [Academy Award for Best Supporting Actress|Best Actress in a Supporting Role] (Maureen Stapleton)
* [Academy Award for Best Cinematography|Best Cinematography] ([Vittorio Storaro]) 
* [Academy Award for Directing|Best Director] (Warren Beatty)
and was nominated for:
* [Academy Award for Best Actor|Best Actor in a Leading Role] (Warren Beatty)
* [Academy Award for Best Supporting Actor|Best Actor in a Supporting Role] (Jack Nicholson)
* [Academy Award for Best Actress|Best Actress in a Leading Role] (Diane Keaton)
* [Academy Award for Best Art Direction|Best Art Direction-Set Decoration]
* [Academy Award for Costume Design|Best Costume Design]
* [Academy Award for Film Editing|Best Film Editing]
* [Academy Award for Best Picture|Best Picture]
* [Academy Award for Sound|Best Sound] 
* [Academy Award for Writing Original Screenplay|Best Writing, Screenplay Written Directly for the Screen].

==Miscellaneous==

During filming, Beatty lectured his [Russia]n [extra (drama)|extra]s on the [capitalism|capitalist] [exploitation] of labour, attempting to inspire them. According to the [magazine] ''[Total Film]'' in [2004], this was the 4th "dumbest decision in movie history": the extras duly went on [strike_action|strike], demanding higher [wage]s.

In the [American Civil War], Reds was also a term by Union soldiers to phrase the approaching [Confederate Army].

