    <title>The More the Merrier</title>
      <minor />
      <comment>cat</comment>
      <text xml:space="preserve">'''''The More the Merrier''''' is a [1943] comedy film which makes fun of the [World War II] time housing shortage, especially in [Washington, D.C.].  A young woman sublets half of her tiny apartment to a middle aged man, who promptly sublets half of his half to a young man.  Romance ensues.  It stars [Jean Arthur], [Joel McCrea], [Stanley Clements], [Charles Coburn] and [Richard Gaines].

The movie was written by [Richard Flournoy], [Lewis R. Foster], [Garson Kanin] (uncredited), [Frank Ross] and [Robert Russell].  It was directed by [George Stevens].

It won the [Academy Award for Best Supporting Actor] (Charles Coburn) and was nominated for [Academy Award for Best Actress|Best Actress in a Leading Role] (Jean Arthur), [Academy Award for Directing|Best Director], [Academy Award for Best Picture|Best Picture], [Academy Award for Best Story|Best Writing, Original Story] and [Academy Award for Writing Original Screenplay|Best Writing, Screenplay].

